pr_review_body:
@sryza raised concerns about this subclassing approach in other discussions around this so we should think through those and consider alternatives before moving forward with this. 

I think the through line of this current approach includes moving the serialization information down to where `OutputDefSnap` is and building the requisite data-structures from that in the host process. If this sounds right to others i think its a sign this route has merit, if not then other paths may be better.

One benefit of this over the current approach is it factors this static asset information in to the snapshot so it can be viewed historically and is part of the identity of the graph, which i think makes sense.

Thanks for addressing my previous comments and for adding all these tests! Overall changes look good. I left a few comments though, plus the following suggestions/questions.

What is the message the user gets after the last retry? Could you add a sample output of running a command that is rate limited?

Could you please update the PR description to make it clear how many retries we are making and what is the min/max time for each of them or until we give up retrying?

Now that I'm taking another look at the code, I think we can avoid all the duplicate `try-except(429)` code if we create a retry decorator for 429 exceptions only. Something like the following:
```
def retry_429(func):
    @retry("RateLimitException")
    def wrap():
        try:
            func()
        except:
            raise Exception("RateLimitException")
    return wrap

@retry_429
def list_status():
    raise Exception("429")
```
We can either add it on the existing `_with_retry` methods and move them in the DbfsService, or directly on the methods in `DbfsService`. I don't have a strong preference over one or the other. If we go with the first option, we can even make a single method per dbfs operation, with a `rateLimitRetry` boolean option based on which we do the retry or not (it can default to true).

> Do you know how this will impact cache keys with the argv no longer being deterministic? Iiuc, the local cache `CommandRunner` doesn't know about `bounded.rs` and simply sees the argv has changed.

@Eric-Arellano : The `bounded::CommandRunner` is always configured to be below all cache lookups. This is intended, because cache lookups should always be cheaper than actually running a process, and so aren't throttled/bounded.

It definitely is a bit fidgety though... the composition of `CommandRunner`s is powerful, but important to stack just-so.

@dkarp0 Thanks for the patch. This is a great contribution.

I wrote one comment. How to handle dual licenses is a vexing issue for this tool.

I think it's better to merge the code as is than to make it more complex. I would like to enhance the `README` documentation.

The url in the template call(s) includes wiki/ and the init always adds wiki to the baseURL for cloud instances.

if ("atlassian.net" in url or "jira.com" in url) and ("/wiki" not in url):
       url = AtlassianRestAPI.url_joiner(url, "/wiki")
def get_content_template(self, template_id):
       url = "wiki/rest/api/template/{template_id}".format(template_id=template_id)
       
This pr fixes this correctly.

@bklebel could you please remove method `check_errors` since, for SCPI instruments, it is provided by `Instrument` class ?
I would replace also `super(Keithley2000, self)` with `super()`
For the rest, it looks good to me.

I think it would be simpler to handle this in a more general case. After we set `typ = codegen.UnwrapType(type)`, we could put 
```go
if union, ok := typ.(*schema.UnionType); ok {
  typ = reduceUnion(union, value)
}
```

Reduce union would look like
```
// reduceUnion returns the element type in union that bests fits value.
// If more than one type fits, reduceUnion will return the first type in union.Elements.
// If no type fits, union.DefaultType is returned. The default type may be `nil`.
func reduceUnion(union *schema.UnionType, value resource.PropertyValue) schema.Type
```

`UnionType.Discriminator` is optional, so we will need to reduce based on the shape of the value, not just on the discriminator.

This looks good to me.
Thanks @prabhat00155 for the good work.

@datumbox does my comment addresses your reservations?
